<div1 type="letter">

<note type="curatorial">54-1</note>
<note type="curatorial">Neihardt Collection</note>
<note type="curatorial">3</note>

<fw>Indiana University<lb/>
Bloomington, Indiana</fw>

<opener>
<dateline>May 16, 1962</dateline>
<address>
<addrLine>Mr. John G. Neihardt</addrLine>
<addrLine>English Department</addrLine>
<addrLine>University of Missouri</addrLine>
<addrLine>Columbia, Missouri</addrLine>
</address>

<salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt: </salute></opener>

<p>I have just discovered <hi rend="underline">Black Elk Speaks</hi> (in the new Bison paperback 
edition).
</p>
<p>It is a great reading experience and a book, like so few others, that I 
am sure I will go back and back to many times.</p>

<p>It has all the things that one finds in lasting literature-- humor, love, 
hate, tragedy. Moreover, it is a piece of true American literature--one that I 
shall hope to use in my own teaching in the future.</p>

<p>If Black Elk were living, and I am sure he can no longer be, I should want 
you to pay my respects and my admiration to him when next you saw him. I should 
hope that you would tell him for me that if the following of literature is in any 
way worthwhile, it is surely in the telling and preservation of such stories as this.</p>

<closer><salute>Very sincerely,</salute>
<signed>David Remley</signed>
The English Office</closer>


</div1>
